<section class="block-section story">
  <span class="section-tag">Story</span>
  <h2>Why this block matters</h2>
  <p class="sub">Last protected drafting day. Plus the rehearsal for a defense format the year hasn't used yet.</p>
  <p><strong>First move: the last protected drafting time.</strong> The <a href="/units/unit-5/assessment-water-stakeholders/">Position Paper</a> needs to land tomorrow with all four parts working — Background (the hydrology + the dispute frame, in your stakeholder's terms), Position (what your stakeholder claims and why), Acknowledge Competing Concerns (the strongest opposing position, stated fairly), and Recommendation (what your stakeholder would propose, with one explicit concession). Mr. Ignash is conferencing through the first 45 minutes — come find him if a section isn't working. The four rubric gates to check one more time: <strong>voice-match T/T</strong> (does this sound like your stakeholder, not you?), <strong>stakeholder specificity K/U</strong> (specific person, place, evidence — not generic categories?), <strong>AI Doc K/U</strong> (substantive log, not "I used AI for help"?), and the <strong>negotiation-move C</strong> signal (an explicit concession or proposed compromise inside the Recommendation?).</p>
  <p><strong>Second move: Roundtable rehearsal.</strong> Tomorrow isn't a defense (one student answering a panel's questions) — it's a <em>negotiation</em>. Six stakeholders at a table, all with competing claims, speaking <em>to each other</em>. Each opens with a statement. Then the table tries to negotiate — looking for legitimate compromise without abandoning core stances. That's a different speaking move than U1's NASA Committee, U2's planning-audience share-out, or U4's Policy Panel Q&A. You can't predict every challenge, but you can predict the <em>shape</em> of them — and you can rehearse responding without strawmanning.</p>
  <p>The trial-arm split surfaces one more time today: Section A rehearses against their own Boodle (or a peer's Boodle if cross-testing); Section B against the Flint Stakeholder Voice tutor; Section C against a peer reading aloud from the paper Stakeholder Profile Pack. All three sections are doing the same rehearsal move — different scaffolds, same skill.</p>
</section>

