<section class="block-section do">
  <span class="section-tag">Do</span>
  <h2>Today's work — choose one path</h2>
  <p class="sub">All four paths end with a submitted-ready draft + an opening statement + 3 anticipated challenges with responses.</p>
  <div class="choice-intro">
    <strong>Learning Intention:</strong> I have predicted at least 3 competing stakeholder positions, prepared responses to at least 4 likely challenges, and identified one concession I'm willing to make + one I'm not.
  </div>
  <div class="choice-board">
    <div class="choice">
      <div class="choice-letter">A</div>
      <div class="choice-title">Drafting block + Stakeholder Voice rehearsal (default)</div>
      <div class="choice-detail">45 min finishing the Position Paper → 30 min rehearsing your opening statement + 3-4 challenge responses with your section's <a href="/ai-partners/stakeholder-voice/">Stakeholder Voice</a> scaffold (your own Boodle, the Flint tutor, or a peer reading from the paper Profile Pack). Push for the <em>strongest</em> challenge in rehearsal — that's what makes Block 9 feel manageable.</div>
      <span class="udl-tag">Solo + paired · Default</span>
    </div>
    <div class="choice">
      <div class="choice-letter">B</div>
      <div class="choice-title">Roundtable readiness — 4 challenges + concession map (stretch)</div>
      <div class="choice-detail">For students whose draft is already clean. Spend the block deepening Roundtable prep: prepare responses to 4 likely challenges (not 3), and explicitly map your <strong>concession floor</strong> — what compromises your stakeholder could accept without abandoning core stance, and what they categorically refuse. The concession map is the C-rubric edge most students miss.</div>
      <span class="udl-tag">Solo · Stretch</span>
    </div>
    <div class="choice">
      <div class="choice-letter">C</div>
      <div class="choice-title">Hydrologist or Source Evaluator on a specific evidence question (choice)</div>
      <div class="choice-detail">If one piece of evidence in your Background or Position section feels weak, open the <a href="/ai-partners/the-hydrologist/">Hydrologist</a> (for hydrology / case-mechanics questions) or the <a href="/ai-partners/the-source-evaluator/">Source Evaluator</a> (for source-credibility / OPVL questions). Document the exchange — this is your final <a href="/foundations/ai-documentation-protocol/">AI Doc</a> entry for the Position Paper.</div>
      <span class="udl-tag">Solo · Choice</span>
    </div>
    <div class="choice">
      <div class="choice-letter">D</div>
      <div class="choice-title">Peer-help — concession vs. capitulation (practice)</div>
      <div class="choice-detail">This is the C-rubric edge most students miss. A real concession concedes a specific point on substance ("you're right that the 2018 verdict didn't account for the failed 2017 monsoon — I'd support reopening the timing question"). A capitulation abandons your stakeholder's core stance ("okay, you're right, my farmers should just take less water"). If the line is fuzzy, come to the peer-help table with one anticipated challenge; Mr. Ignash + a peer will walk through what a real concession would sound like.</div>
      <span class="udl-tag">Pairs · Practice</span>
    </div>
  </div>
</section>

